**Describe your issue**

Upgrading from version 3.4.0 -> 3.4.1 gives me issues with data-[] applying styles. Some still apply but many do not.

Given that FF only recently gained support for `:has` ‚Äî it's necessary to split `:has` rules when optimizing defaults because entire rules will be invalidated rather than just the simple selector containing `:has`.

**If you're not using `experimental.optimizeUniversalDefaults` you're not affected**

---

Before:
```
:is(.ring-1, .has-\[\:checked\]\:ring-1:has(:checked)) {
  --tw-ring-inset: ;
  --tw-ring-offset-width: 0px;
  --tw-ring-offset-color: #fff;
  --tw-ring-color: #3b82f680;
  --tw-ring-offset-shadow: 0 0 #0000;
  --tw-ring-shadow: 0 0 #0000;
  --tw-shadow: 0 0 #0000;
  --tw-shadow-colored: 0 0 #0000;
}
```

After:
```
.ring-1 {
  --tw-ring-inset: ;
  --tw-ring-offset-width: 0px;
  --tw-ring-offset-color: #fff;
  --tw-ring-color: #3b82f680;
  --tw-ring-offset-shadow: 0 0 #0000;
  --tw-ring-shadow: 0 0 #0000;
  --tw-shadow: 0 0 #0000;
  --tw-shadow-colored: 0 0 #0000;
}
.has-\[\:checked\]\:ring-1:has(:checked) {
  --tw-ring-inset: ;
  --tw-ring-offset-width: 0px;
  --tw-ring-offset-color: #fff;
  --tw-ring-color: #3b82f680;
  --tw-ring-offset-shadow: 0 0 #0000;
  --tw-ring-shadow: 0 0 #0000;
  --tw-shadow: 0 0 #0000;
  --tw-shadow-colored: 0 0 #0000;
}
```

**Reproduction URL**

https://codesandbox.io/p/devbox/jovial-sound-sgqddr?file=%2Fapp%2Fglobals.css%3A4%2C19

**Describe your issue**

The attribute selectors in the following rule of the CSS reset have a specificity of 0-1-0:
```css
[type=button], [type=reset], [type=submit], button {
    -webkit-appearance: button;
    background-color: initial;
    background-image: none
}
```

The issue arises when importing a CSS file with rules of matching specificity:
```css
/* globals.css */
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
@import "./example-button.css";
```

```css
/* example-button.css */
.example-button {
  background-color: blue;
}
```

No matter the order, the styles from `@tailwind base` are appended after the imported file and take over the rules that use a CSS class selector.

I know this has been raised before, but I haven‚Äôt seen any discussion about an easy possible fix being the `:where()` selector there to lower the specificity to 0-0-0:

```css
:where([type=button], [type=reset], [type=submit], button) {
    -webkit-appearance: button;
    background-color: initial;
    background-image: none
}
```

This way, `@tailwind base` won‚Äôt impact any custom styles, while components and utilities work as is.

***Additional context***
I‚Äôm one of the Radix Themes maintainers. While we don‚Äôt use Tailwind to build Radix Themes itself, one of the goals we have is to provide a great experience for people using any styling technology for their custom styles, including Tailwind users. Ideally, this would ‚Äújust work‚Äù. However, it doesn‚Äôt, and although workarounds exist, we found that the vast majority of people [struggle to debug this intuitively](https://github.com/radix-ui/themes/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aclosed+label%3Atailwind).

I also think that fixing this would improve the situation for everyone, as the scenario that my reproduction URL shows is very basic and plausible in many codebases where hand-rolled styles are used hand in hand with Tailwind.

This PR fixes an issue where we assumed that `(`, `)`, `[` and `]` were already properly escaped. This wasn't the case, let's fix it.

This is also going to be a nice DX improvement for people using file based routers where the files and folders can contain any of the following characters: `()[]`

In this PR, we will make sure to escape those characters, and we will also ensure that we don't double escape them if you already escaped them yourselfs. This means that the following 2 snippets will be equivalent:

```js
/** @type {import\('tailwindcss').Config} */
module.exports = {
  content: [
    "./src/1.html",
    "./src/(test)/2.html",
    "./src/[test]/3.html",
    "./src/[test]/(test)/4.html",
    "./src/*/(test)/4.html",
  ],
  theme: {
    extend: {},
  },
  plugins: [],
};
```

```js
/** @type {import\('tailwindcss').Config} */
module.exports = {
  content: [
    "./src/1.html",
    "./src/\\(test\\)/2.html",
    "./src/\\[test\\]/3.html",
    "./src/\\[test\\]/\\(test\\)/4.html",
    "./src/*/\\(test\\)/4.html",
  ],
  theme: {
    extend: {},
  },
  plugins: [],
};
```

Fixes: #12708
